            <div1 type="letter">
                <pb facs="nei.j4b.1.53-54"/>
                <note type="curatorial">53</note>
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                
                <opener>
                    
                    <dateline>11 p.m. March 4. [18]</dateline>
                    
                </opener>
                
                <p>Have just come back from reading at the auditorium in Wheeler Hall. Had a nice crowd
                (about 250 to 300). Gayley introduced me &amp; spoke of me as an eminent young
                poet who could no longer be questioned. Spoke of "Hugh" in glowing terms.
                People were very attentive &amp; a good number spoke to me afterward &amp; said nice
                things. a girl's school (sort of West Coast Vassar) wants me to give a reading there - probably Wednesday or Thursday. If there's good money in it, I'll stay for it. The Janitor of Wheeler 
                -S talks of me as one of the five or six best poets in america</p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4b.1.53-54"/>
                <note type="curatorial">54</note>
                
                <p>Hall saw me &amp; said: "Hello, Johnnie, I haven't seen you for 28 years. Used to go
                to school with you at the Irving School in K.C.!" Josie Terch was there,
                &amp; a Miss Hamilton who knew Grace &amp; Lulu at Wayne. Also, a Mr. Olson from Wisner. 
                I consider the reading a success here. 
                Have been very comfortable at this club-nice easy place to be. Have to take dinner
                with friends of the Howards here tomorrow &amp; will read a few lyrics to the party Have to do it to be decent. Want to be at home.</p>
                <signed>Lovingly, Jno.</signed> 
                <postscript><p>Damn public stunts! I'd rather be with my people, working. Nothing counts but that.</p></postscript> 

            </div1>
            
